Does the reproduction state,gender and age of an animal affect whether or not the animal is adopted?

Ru

10/8/2018

Introduction

The main purpose of this analysis is to explore how to deal with datasets that violate the normal statistical assumptions using Generalized Linear Models.

Briefly, in generalized linear models, the response variable follows an exponential family distribution with mean \(\mu\) which is a function of a usually non-linear beta. This paper will specifically be going through logistic regression - a statistical technique that is used to explain the relationship between one response binary variable \(y\) and one or more predictor variables.

The dataset

The dataset belongs to Austin Animal Center and contained 92698 animals including cats, dogs, birds, and livestock. This dataset had 12 variables including the Animal ID, name of the animal, date-time, and month year (which I later found out had the same information), date of birth, outcome type, outcome subtype, animal type, sex upon outcome, age upon outcome, breed and color of the animal.

In order to find these variables and what type of variables they are, I used the str function. This shows the structure of the dataset including information about the number of observations, the number of variables and the type of variables. From the output given, all the variables are factors so there’s definitely going to be a need to clean up these variables before we can analyze the dataset.

Predictors

Age

I was interested in finding out the effect of sex, age and gender on whether or not a dog was adopted. Initially, I thought I could easily use the Sex.upon.Outcome, and Age.upon.Outcome variables. However, as I learnt more about my data, the dataset proved I would not want to use these variables as they are.

Reasons why I would not use the Age.upon.Outcome variable:

• It’s a categorical variable. While this may not be an issue if we were dealing with another statistical model, it would definitely not be in our best interest to use the Age.upon.Outcome variable. Using the group_by function in dplyr, I found out there were 49 different ages of the animal.
Age.upon.Outcome n
-1 years 1
0 years 118
1 day 184
1 month 4060
1 week 500
1 weeks 618

These ages were also in different categories eg. 184 animals were 1 day old and 117 animals were 0years old. Interestingly, we had one animal that was -1year old. One might wonder, so how different are the animals who are one day old from the animals that are 0 years old?

Besides this weird dilemma, it just makes conceptual sense to use age as a number… and therefore a continuous variable as it conventionally is. Let’s clean age up a little bit.

Clean up of Age:

The dataset had a DateTime variable that showed the day an outcome happened to an animal, and the Date.of.Birth of the animal so I subtracted the DateTime from the Date.Of.Birth and created a new variable Age_in_years:

#dates 
#change factors to date 
Austin_Animals$DateTime =as.Date(Austin_Animals$DateTime, format = "%m/%d/%Y")
Austin_Animals$Date.of.Birth = as.Date(Austin_Animals$Date.of.Birth, format = "%m/%d/%Y")

#get the difference between the two dates 
Austin_Animals$Age_in_years = as.numeric(difftime(as.Date(Austin_Animals$DateTime),
                    as.Date(Austin_Animals$Date.of.Birth),unit="weeks"))/52.25

Sex

There were four levels of sex.upon. Outcome: 1. Neutered Male 2. Intact Male 3. Spayed Female 4. Intact Female

I added a new variable, reproduction_state, which tells us whether the animal was fixed(i.e intact) or not fixed(in this case, either neutered or spayed). I also added the variable gender which tells us whether the animal is female or male.

Splitting this variable into two different variables enables us to have a better understanding on whether the reproduction state of an animal affects whether or not it is adopted depending on its gender. Null or unknown values of the animal’s sex were removed.

Austin_Animals = Austin_Animals%>%
  mutate(reproduction_state = ifelse(str_detect(Austin_Animals$Sex.upon.Outcome,"Intact"),"Fixed","Not Fixed"),gender = ifelse(str_detect(Austin_Animals$Sex.upon.Outcome,"Female"),"Female","Male"))%>%
  filter(Sex.upon.Outcome != "Unknown")%>%
  filter(Sex.upon.Outcome != "NULL")

The response variable:Outcome Type

This is the response variable and tells us the outcome of the particular animal. There were eight levels of outcome types with most of the animals at Austin Texas being adopted. 8 of the animals outcome type.

The purpose of this analysis is to learn more about binary logistic regression. However, our response variable has 9 variables:

Now what?

I changed Adoption and Rto-Adopt level to be Adopted and the rest as Not Adopted so as to remain with only two levels for my data.

One might wonder why I did not filter out the rest and this is because removing all those levels would eventually leave us with just a few options and bias our estimates for the regression coeefients. I do understand that some bias will be created as one can argue that keeping the “transferred” level" will also add some bias in the model as we do not know whether the transferred animals were later adopted or not, but as of the time the dataset was created, the animal had not been adopted so the bias caused by this would not be as high as the bias caused by totally removing the levels of our factor.

Data Models

Checking correlation between variables

I used Cramer’s values to check for possible multi-colinearity between my predictor variable before building the model:

adoption Age_in_years reproduction_state gender
adoption 1.0000000 0.4517300 0.5472867 0.0151724
Age_in_years 0.4517300 1.0000000 0.4993887 0.3043011
reproduction_state 0.5472867 0.4993887 1.0000000 0.0264859
gender 0.0151724 0.3043011 0.0264859 1.0000000

What do these Cramer’s values mean?

Crammer’s Value show the strength of the relationships between our variables. Values close to 0 determine little relationship between variables, values close to 1 determine strong correlation. In this case, we see that the predictors with the strongest relationship with the adoption outcome are the reproduction_state and Age_in_years. Crammers V 0.55 and 0.45 respectively. I will therefore use these predictors to build my model.

Visualizing logistic regression

From the visualization, there is a pretty weak relationship between our predictors and our response variable. However, we can tell that the probability non-fixed dogs decreases as they get older. The probability of fixed dogs being adopted increases as they age. This probability is still lower than than of dogs that are not fixed.

We can also see that there are more fixed animals at younger ages.

Building a model with Logistic Regression

Logistic regression is a non-linear regression model that is used to measure categorical response variables. Binary logistic regression is used when there are two possible response outcomes (in this case, Adopted, or Not Adopted).

Logistic regression can be used to:

Model the probability of an event occuring depending on the values of the independent variables Estimate the probability that an event occurs for a randomly selected observation versus the probability that the event does not occur. Predict the effect of a series of variables on a binary response variable. In this case, it would be working just like simple and multiple linear regression. Classify observations by estimating the probability that an observation is in a particular category(such as adopted or not adopted in this case)

Why logistic regression:

Reasons why we use binary logistic regression rather than linear regression: 1. Non-normal error terms 2. Non–constant error variance 3. Constraints on response functions- This occurs because when measuring the binary response, we only have two outcomes. 1- something occurs or 0- nothing occurs. Therefore, when measuring the response, lets picture it as measuring the likelihood that something occurs or does not occur. This is almost the same as measuring the probability that something happens and in this situation, we cannot have a more than 1 chance that something happens or a less than 0 chance. Characteristics of the logistic regression function: 1. Is bounded between 0 and 1 2. Has a characteristic sigmoidal (S) shape 3. Approaches 0 and 1 asymptotically.

I separated my data into training and test data by getting a 70% sample of it and making it the training data and using 30% to make it the test data.

train = clean_animals%>%
  sample_frac(0.70)
test = anti_join(clean_animals, train, by = 'Animal.ID')

Logistic regression predicts the true proportion of success, \(\pi\) at any value of the explanatory variable \(y = # of 1's/# of trials\) \(\pi = proportion of successes (1's)\)

logtrain = glm(is_adopted~reproduction_state*Age_in_years, data= train, family=binomial)
summary(logtrain)

Our final model is:

\(logit(\pi) = -2.28 + 3.93reproduction\_stateNotFixed -0.03Age\_in\_years - 0.18reproduction\_stateNot Fixed:Age\_in\_years\)

After building our model,we need to assess how accurately the model predicts whether or not an animal is adopted.

Assessing the model

glm_probs = data.frame(probs = predict(logtrain, 
                                       newdata = test, 
                                       type="response"))
glm_pred = glm_probs %>%
  mutate(pred = ifelse(probs>.80, "Adopted", "Not"))

glm_pred = cbind(test, glm_pred)

glm_pred %>% 
  count(pred, is_adopted) %>%
  spread(is_adopted, n, fill = 0)
## # A tibble: 2 x 3
##   pred      `0`   `1`
##   <chr>   <dbl> <dbl>
## 1 Adopted   669  3557
## 2 Not      2965  2348
glm_pred %>%
  summarize(score = mean(pred == is_adopted),
            recip = mean(pred != is_adopted))
##   score recip
## 1     0     1

According to the confusion matrix, our model is only 33% accurate. Pretty dissapointing heh? In the next post, we’ll talk about choosing the best predictors for our model to increase this accuracy rate.
